article.headline: Vandy thrashes Wisc.-Milwaukee behind Anderson
article.linkText: Vandy bounces back from loss with runaway win
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A loss isn't always a bad thing, as
ninth-ranked Vanderbilt might have proven.

	   Rebounding from a disappointing weekend setback against No. 6
Purdue, the Commodores got off to a strong start and finished with
a 98-51 victory Tuesday night over Wisconsin-Milwaukee.

	   Abi Ramsey scored 15 of her career-high 18 points in the first
half, and Vanderbilt (5-1) led 56-13 at halftime, the biggest
margin at the break in the program's history. Vanderbilt led Towson
State by 40 points at the half in a 105-46 victory Feb. 21, 1995.

	   ''I think I had struggled with when to shoot, when not to
shoot,'' said Ramsey, who hit a couple of 3-pointers in the final
45 seconds of the Commodores' 73-66 loss to Purdue.

	   Ramsey hit five treys, all in the first half, Tuesday.

	   ''I guess I realized toward the end of the Purdue game that was
a strength for us,'' he said. ''I guess it gave me the confidence I
needed.''

	   Chantelle Anderson had 22 points and Jenni Benningfield 17 for
Vanderbilt.

	   Wisconsin-Milwaukee (3-5) went more than nine minutes without a
point in the first half, allowing the Commodores to stretch an 11-7
lead to 35-7 with seven minutes to play.

	   ''That was part of my fear,'' Wisconsin-Milwaukee Coach Sandy
Botham said. ''Them coming off a loss to a team I'm sure they
thought they should have beaten, then getting back home and being
mad, and just hoping we can handle it.

	   ''But I think our kids honestly believed we could beat them.''

	   Vanderbilt went on to lead by as many as 54 points, going ahead
81-27 on a Nicole Jules' basket with 10:16 remaining.

	   ''I think this game was about us, not who we were playing,''
Vanderbilt guard Ashley McElhiney said. ''We were going to make
adjustments and get better.''

	   Kimberly Becker scored 14 points to lead Wisconsin-Milwaukee,
and Maria Viall added 13.
